import java.io.*;  // Import necessary classes to handle streams, sockets etc., like BufferedReader/Writer...etc in NodeJS environment and JavaScript also provides Socket class java_52221_SocketServer_A03 default which can be used here for creating a TCP Server using this example as well..So no external dependencies required  
                      
public abstract class SimpleTCPServer {  // Declare Abstract Class to ensure our server will always implement the same methods. This acts like blueprint from where all servers are going to inherit their behavior and structure (methods). It should be a good practice for large scale applications as it helps us in maintaining code consistency across different parts of your program
    private int port;  // Declare necessary variables, set them based on use case i.e., what is the server supposed do when someone connects to our socket? which actions are done by connecting client and so this data should be kept inside class as a field (instance variable).   This could also include if it's going to handle multiple clients or not etc..
    private ServerSocket socketserver;  // Declare required server variables. We will need an instance of the socket, which is created by passing 'port number', and we can have our own function for starting this up when needed in a real application setting (like startServer() method)
    
   public SimpleTCPServer(int port){// Constructor to set initial values  // Initialize server with parameters: what IP/Port should be used, how many clients it will handle at the same time etc. This is where we setup our socket and assign variables inside constructor of Java program for setting up servers
        this.port = port;    ///Setting an initialization value to a variable here means creating object during runtime 
                            // (in case when you want more than one server, that have different ports) or at the start-up   if we just write once into field and reuse it throughout entire program..or in another way.        So be creative while declaring variables inside constructor to avoid any mistake which could lead your code not run properly later
                             socketserver = new ServerSocket(port);    ///Here, you create a server socket on the specific port number  //Server is set up here and can listen for requests from clients (connected devices) at that particular point in time.      If it's going to handle multiple connections/request we will have separate instance of this as well
                           }  
     public void start(){ ///Method responsible with starting the server-listening on established socket port by calling a new thread and thus can continue operations while waiting for client requests,  // Start method - When you call it (startServer() function), make your program wait till someone connects to our TCP Server. Once somebody is connected then we start receiving/transmitting data from the connecting clients using BufferedReader & Writers
        new HandlerThread(this).start();   ///Handling Thread, where all requests coming in via sockets will be passed on and processed by this thread  // Starts a handler that waits for incoming messages (request) at server side. Once it gets any request from client then the 'run' method of message handling class is called which handles both clients & their respective data transfer
                            }     ///This code should stay inside start() as long until someone makes connections and requests - this way, our TCP Server will be operational  // The loop in main function has to do a lot more but it serves the purpose here. So keep going with your creative coding!   Be sure you have created separate threads for clients (which are connected) & server too
    }     ///And also as per socket programming model we must implement some way of getting data from/to client and then pass this on to message handling thread, which in turn can handle the incoming messages or request. In future when it comes about TCP communication between two devices - you will need something like SocketStream classes for that purpose